      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The Maillard reaction is a complex chemical process between amino acids and reducing sugars that creates brown pigments and savory flavors. Chemically, this involves the amino group of an amino acid reacting with the carbonyl group of a reducing sugar to form glycosylamines, which then proceed through a series of reactions—including Strecker degradation and enolization—to produce final brown products and volatile flavor compounds. For you to achieve proper browning on the exam, you generally need to aim for a temperature range of **140°C to 165°C (285°F to 330°F)**, as reactions below this range proceed too slowly.",
